00:52:20,800 --> 00:52:21,800
Good morning.

962
00:52:21,900 --> 00:52:24,700
If the President proceeds
with this plan,

963
00:52:25,500 --> 00:52:28,500
what in your view would constitute
a victory?

964
00:52:29,300 --> 00:52:32,500
What is the definition of victory
in this contest?

965
00:52:32,600 --> 00:52:33,900
Yes.

966
00:52:34,100 --> 00:52:36,500
A military victory
in the traditional sense

967
00:52:36,700 --> 00:52:38,100
is not what we are seeking.

968
00:52:38,700 --> 00:52:41,200
To eliminate
every last Vietcong guerilla,

969
00:52:41,400 --> 00:52:45,300
could require as many
as half a million men

970
00:52:45,500 --> 00:52:46,500
and five years...

971
00:52:46,700 --> 00:52:49,900
N-n-no one, no one's considerin
those kinda numbers, no one.

972
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:52,900
Our objective is to reach
a stalemate whereby

973
00:52:53,000 --> 00:52:56,600
we are attriting the enemy faster

974
00:52:56,700 --> 00:52:58,900
than he can replace his loses,

975
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:01,600
this is the so-called
cross-over point.

976
00:53:01,700 --> 00:53:03,300
And how many men will this require?

977
00:53:03,500 --> 00:53:05,600
A substantially smaller number.

978
00:53:05,800 --> 00:53:09,700
Depending on how
the North Vietnamese respond.

979
00:53:09,800 --> 00:53:11,700
Well,
might they respond by sending in,

980
00:53:11,800 --> 00:53:15,000
say, 100,000 troops?

981
00:53:15,100 --> 00:53:16,900
We regard this as unlikely.

982
00:53:17,100 --> 00:53:20,300
Well, it's less than half the men
they have under arms.

983
00:53:20,400 --> 00:53:21,400
Well, it's certainly possible,

984
00:53:21,600 --> 00:53:23,600
they already have 50,000 men
down there.

985
00:53:23,800 --> 00:53:26,500
And to achieve the ten
to one superiority?

986
00:53:26,700 --> 00:53:28,300
Which I understand is barely adequate

987
00:53:28,500 --> 00:53:32,000
for conventional forces
in a guerilla situation.

988
00:53:32,900 --> 00:53:34,400
How many troops would be required

989
00:53:34,600 --> 00:53:36,500
to meet this possible threat?

990
00:53:37,700 --> 00:53:39,900
As I said, this would be unlikely.

991
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:42,500
One million troops,
is that not correct, General?

992
00:53:44,400 --> 00:53:51,500
You see, we would need
one million men in Vietnam.

993
00:53:59,000 --> 00:53:59,700
Excuse me

994
00:53:59,800 --> 00:54:00,900
Clark...

995
00:54:01,300 --> 00:54:02,200
I can't tell you how grateful

996
00:54:02,400 --> 00:54:04,500
I am to finely have an alley
at the barricades.

997
00:54:04,600 --> 00:54:07,500
Well, it's just what makes sense,
George.

998
00:54:07,700 --> 00:54:10,200
Not to Bob McNamara but to me.

999
00:54:10,300 --> 00:54:11,600
A million men was straight-out

1000
00:54:11,700 --> 00:54:14,200
of your memo of October last year.

1001
00:54:14,400 --> 00:54:17,000
An impressively persuasive document
in my opinion.

1002
00:54:17,200 --> 00:54:18,500
All sixty-seven pages of it.

1003
00:54:18,600 --> 00:54:19,100
Well...

1004
00:54:19,300 --> 00:54:21,800
I haven't shown much restraint
on the subject, it's true.

1005
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:22,800
If he brought you in,

1006
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:26,300
it must be because I'm like
an old broken record now.

1007
00:54:26,800 --> 00:54:28,200
Well, then that'd be two of us.

1008
00:54:28,400 --> 00:54:30,600
Scratchy and irritating as hell.

1009
00:54:30,800 --> 00:54:31,900
Good day, George.

1010
00:54:33,600 --> 00:54:34,200
Yeah?

1011
00:54:34,400 --> 00:54:36,700
The Vista Volunteers are here
for the pictures, Mr. President.

1012
00:54:36,800 --> 00:54:37,700
All right,
tell em I'll be out in a minute.

1013
00:54:37,800 --> 00:54:40,200
And tell Goodwin
I wanna see him right after.

1014
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:45,400
I called Marg soon
